# üèÜ How to Speak Like a Senior Engineer

Use these phrases:

* ‚ÄúI prefer **user-facing locators**‚Äù
* ‚ÄúI isolate UI using **API mocks**‚Äù
* ‚ÄúI avoid hard waits completely‚Äù
* ‚ÄúI design **CI-friendly parallel frameworks**‚Äù

In **Playwright**, **selectors** are used to **locate elements on the page** so that you can perform actions (click, type, assert, etc.).

üëâ **Interview-friendly definition**

> *Selectors in Playwright are ways to identify web elements. Playwright promotes user-facing, resilient selectors with built-in auto-waiting and retry logic.*

---

# üîπ Types of Selectors in Playwright (IMPORTANT)

## 1Ô∏è‚É£ Role Selectors (‚≠ê BEST & MOST RECOMMENDED)

Based on **ARIA roles** (how users and screen readers see the page).

```ts
page.getByRole('button', { name: 'Login' })
```

‚úÖ Stable
‚úÖ Accessibility friendly
‚úÖ Interviewer favorite

**Examples**

```ts
page.getByRole('textbox', { name: 'Username' })
page.getByRole('link', { name: 'Home' })
```

---

## 2Ô∏è‚É£ Text Selectors

Locate elements using **visible text**.

```ts
page.getByText('Submit')
```

Partial match:

```ts
page.getByText('Submit', { exact: false })
```

---

## 3Ô∏è‚É£ Label Selectors

Used for form fields associated with `<label>`.

```ts
page.getByLabel('Email')
```

‚úÖ Very reliable for inputs

---

## 4Ô∏è‚É£ Placeholder Selectors

Based on input placeholder text.

```ts
page.getByPlaceholder('Enter password')
```

---

## 5Ô∏è‚É£ Test ID Selectors (BEST PRACTICE)

Used when developers add `data-testid`.

```ts
page.getByTestId('login-btn')
```

HTML:

```html
<button data-testid="login-btn">Login</button>
```

---

# üîπ CSS & XPath Selectors (Less Preferred)

## 6Ô∏è‚É£ CSS Selector

```ts
page.locator('#username')
page.locator('.login-btn')
```

‚ö†Ô∏è Use only when user-facing selectors not available

---

## 7Ô∏è‚É£ XPath Selector (‚ùå Avoid if possible)

```ts
page.locator('//button[text()="Login"]')
```

‚ùå Fragile
‚ùå Hard to maintain

---

# üîπ Locator API (VERY IMPORTANT CONCEPT)

In Playwright, **selectors are used through locators**.

```ts
const loginBtn = page.getByRole('button', { name: 'Login' });
await loginBtn.click();
```

### Why locators are powerful?

* Auto-wait
* Auto-retry
* Re-evaluated on every action

---

# üîπ Chained & Filtered Selectors (Advanced)

## Filter by text inside element

```ts
page.locator('tr').filter({ hasText: 'John' })
```

## Parent-Child relation

```ts
page.locator('tr', {
  has: page.locator('td', { hasText: 'John' })
})
```

---

# üîπ nth Selector (Use Carefully)

```ts
page.locator('button').nth(0)
```

‚ö†Ô∏è Can break if UI changes

---

# üîπ Shadow DOM Selector

Playwright handles Shadow DOM automatically:

```ts
page.locator('my-component >> button')
```

---

# üîπ Selector Priority (INTERVIEW ANSWER)

**Best ‚Üí Worst order**

1. `getByRole`
2. `getByLabel`
3. `getByPlaceholder`
4. `getByText`
5. `getByTestId`
6. CSS
7. XPath

---

# üîπ Common Interview Questions

### ‚ùì Difference between `locator()` and `page.$()`?

| locator()   | page.$()   |
| ----------- | ---------- |
| Auto-wait   | No wait    |
| Retry       | No retry   |
| Recommended | Deprecated |

---

### ‚ùì Why Playwright selectors are more stable?

* User-centric
* Accessibility-based
* Auto-wait & retry

---

# üèÜ How to Answer in Interview (One-Liner)

> ‚ÄúPlaywright encourages **user-facing selectors like role, label, and text** instead of brittle XPath or CSS, which makes tests stable and maintainable.‚Äù

