Below is a **clear, interview-ready explanation of OOPS concepts used in Playwright (JavaScript)** with **practical automation examples**.
This is exactly how you can explain it as an **SDET / Automation Engineer**.

---

## 1Ô∏è‚É£ Encapsulation (Most Used in Playwright)

### üëâ What is it?

Encapsulation means **binding data (locators) and behavior (actions)** together and **hiding internal implementation**.

### üëâ Where used in Playwright?

**Page Object Model (POM)**

### ‚úÖ Example: LoginPage.js

```javascript
class LoginPage {
  constructor(page) {
    this.page = page;
    this.usernameInput = page.locator('#username');
    this.passwordInput = page.locator('#password');
    this.loginButton = page.locator('#login');
  }

  async login(username, password) {
    await this.usernameInput.fill(username);
    await this.passwordInput.fill(password);
    await this.loginButton.click();
  }
}

module.exports = LoginPage;
```

### ‚úÖ Test File

```javascript
const LoginPage = require('../pages/LoginPage');

test('Login Test', async ({ page }) => {
  const loginPage = new LoginPage(page);
  await loginPage.login('admin', 'password123');
});
```

üìå **Benefit:**

* Tests don‚Äôt care about locators
* If UI changes ‚Üí update only page class

---

## 2Ô∏è‚É£ Abstraction

### üëâ What is it?

Showing **only essential features** and hiding complex logic.

### üëâ Where used in Playwright?

* Utility methods
* Base page actions
* Reusable workflows

### ‚úÖ Example: BasePage.js

```javascript
class BasePage {
  constructor(page) {
    this.page = page;
  }

  async navigate(url) {
    await this.page.goto(url);
  }

  async click(locator) {
    await locator.click();
  }
}

module.exports = BasePage;
```

### ‚úÖ LoginPage using abstraction

```javascript
const BasePage = require('./BasePage');

class LoginPage extends BasePage {
  constructor(page) {
    super(page);
    this.username = page.locator('#username');
    this.password = page.locator('#password');
    this.loginBtn = page.locator('#login');
  }

  async login(user, pass) {
    await this.username.fill(user);
    await this.password.fill(pass);
    await this.click(this.loginBtn);
  }
}

module.exports = LoginPage;
```

üìå **Benefit:**

* Clean tests
* Common logic reused everywhere

---

## 3Ô∏è‚É£ Inheritance

### üëâ What is it?

One class **inherits properties and methods** of another class.

### üëâ Where used in Playwright?

* BasePage ‚Üí All page classes
* BaseTest ‚Üí Setup/teardown

### ‚úÖ Example

```javascript
class BasePage {
  constructor(page) {
    this.page = page;
  }

  async waitForPageLoad() {
    await this.page.waitForLoadState('networkidle');
  }
}
```

```javascript
class DashboardPage extends BasePage {
  constructor(page) {
    super(page);
    this.header = page.locator('h1');
  }

  async getHeaderText() {
    return await this.header.textContent();
  }
}
```

üìå **Benefit:**

* Avoid code duplication
* Centralized common actions

---

## 4Ô∏è‚É£ Polymorphism

### üëâ What is it?

Same method name but **different behavior** depending on the class.

### üëâ Where used in Playwright?

* Different pages implementing same action differently
* Overriding base methods

### ‚úÖ Example

```javascript
class BasePage {
  async submit() {
    console.log('Submitting base form');
  }
}
```

```javascript
class LoginPage extends BasePage {
  async submit() {
    console.log('Submitting login form');
  }
}
```

```javascript
class RegisterPage extends BasePage {
  async submit() {
    console.log('Submitting registration form');
  }
}
```

üìå **Benefit:**

* Flexible design
* Easy framework extension

---

## 5Ô∏è‚É£ Composition (Very Important for Playwright)

### üëâ What is it?

Using **objects inside other objects** instead of inheritance.

### üëâ Where used?

* Using Page Object inside tests
* Using helper classes (API, Utils)

### ‚úÖ Example

```javascript
class AuthHelper {
  async loginViaAPI(request) {
    const response = await request.post('/login', {
      data: { user: 'admin', pass: '1234' }
    });
    return response.json();
  }
}
```

```javascript
test('UI test with API login', async ({ page, request }) => {
  const auth = new AuthHelper();
  const token = await auth.loginViaAPI(request);

  await page.addInitScript(token => {
    localStorage.setItem('token', token);
  }, token);

  await page.goto('/dashboard');
});
```

üìå **Benefit:**

* Faster tests
* Better separation of concerns

---

## üî• How to Answer in Interview (Short Version)

> ‚ÄúIn Playwright, I use OOPS mainly through Page Object Model.
> Encapsulation helps me hide locators inside page classes.
> Inheritance allows sharing common logic via BasePage.
> Abstraction simplifies test code using reusable methods.
> Polymorphism helps override behavior across pages.
> Composition is used when integrating helpers like API or utilities.‚Äù




